text:
In this task, you will be presented with a sequence of syllables with unique pitches, then a single syllable with a unique pitch.

There are two different tasks you may be asked to do.

The first task is to remember only the syllables in the first sequence, then decide if the following singular syllable was in the first sequence or not.

The second task is to remember only the pitches in the first sequence, then decide if the pitch of the singular syllable was in the first sequence or not.

After hearing both the sequence and the singular syllable, you will be prompted to reply with 'present' or 'absent'.

We will start with some examples.
In this next example, listen to the pitch of the sequence and the following syllable, then reply if the pitch of the syllable was 'present' or 'absent'.
In the past example, the pitch of the 4th syllable was present in the probe stimulus. Let's listen to it again. Don't worry - we know this is challenging!
In the next example, pay special attention to the pitch of the last syllable in the sequence.
The previous example was 'absent', because the pitch of the single syllable was different from the pitch of the last syllable in the sequence. Try a couple more examples on your own.
The previous example was 'absent'
The previous example was 'present'

In this next practice section, you will hear a sequence of syllables with different pitches, a pause, then a single syllable. Your task is to determine whether the syllable itself was present or absent from the sequence.
In the past example, the 4th syllable in the sequence was the same as the singular syllable. Let's listen to it again!
The previous example was 'present'. Try a couple more examples on your own.
The previous example was 'absent'
The previous example was 'absent'

The previous example was 'present'. You are done the introductory trials.

You will now be taken to a practice section with 8 trials. You must get 5/8 trials correct to continue with the rest of the experiment.
